LB845 LB845
2026 2026
LEGISLATURE OF NEBRASKA
ONE HUNDRED NINTH LEGISLATURE
SECOND SESSION
LEGISLATIVE BILL 845
Introduced by Health and Human Services Committee: Hardin, 48,
Chairperson; Ballard, 21; Hansen, 16; Meyer, G., 17; Riepe,
12.
Read first time January 08, 2026
Committee: Health and Human Services
1 A BILL FOR AN ACT relating to public health and welfare; to amend
2 sections 81-6,122, 81-2205, 81-2212, and 81-2226, Reissue Revised
3 Statutes of Nebraska, sections 28-712, 71-561, 71-563, 71-564,
4 71-565, 71-566, and 71-567, Revised Statutes Cumulative Supplement,
5 2024, and section 71-814, Revised Statutes Supplement, 2025; to
6 eliminate an advisory committee of the Nebraska Children's
7 Commission; to rename and change provisions relating to the
8 Alzheimer's Disease and Other Dementia Advisory Council; to redefine
9 terms; to change membership; to change provisions relating to
10 findings and recommendations of the advisory council; to change
11 provisions relating to the State Alzheimer's Plan; to create the
12 Aging, Alzheimer's, and Dementia Advisory Council Fund; to rename
13 the State Advisory Committee on Mental Health Services; to eliminate
14 the Division of Medicaid and Long-Term Care Advisory Committee on
15 Aging; to harmonize provisions; to repeal the original sections; and
16 to outright repeal sections 68-1101, 68-1103, 68-1104, and 68-1106,
17 Reissue Revised Statutes of Nebraska, and section 68-1105, Revised
18 Statutes Cumulative Supplement, 2024.
19 Be it enacted by the people of the State of Nebraska,
-1-

LB845 LB845
2026 2026
1 Section 1. Section 28-712, Revised Statutes Cumulative Supplement,
2 2024, is amended to read:
3 28-712 (1) Upon receipt of a report pursuant to section 28-711, the
4 department shall determine whether to (a) accept the report for
5 traditional response and an investigation pursuant to section 28-713, (b)
6 accept the report for alternative response pursuant to section 28-712.01,
7 (c) accept the report for screening by the Review, Evaluate, and Decide
8 Team to determine eligibility for alternative response, or (d) classify
9 the report as requiring no further action by the department.
10 (2)(a) The Nebraska Children's Commission shall appoint an advisory
11 committee to examine the department's alternative response to reports of
12 child abuse or neglect and to make recommendations to the Legislature,
13 the department, and the commission regarding (i) the receipt and
14 screening of reports of child abuse or neglect by the department, (ii)
15 the ongoing use of alternative response, (iii) the ongoing use of
16 traditional response, and (iv) the provision of services within
17 alternative response and non-court-involved cases to ensure child safety,
18 to reduce the risk of child abuse or neglect, and to engage families. The
19 advisory committee may request, receive, and review data from the
20 department regarding such processes.
21 (b) The members of the advisory committee shall include, but not be
22 limited to, a representative of (i) the department, (ii) law enforcement
23 agencies, (iii) county attorneys or other prosecutors, (iv) the state
24 chapter of child advocacy centers as defined in 34 U.S.C. 20302, (v)
25 attorneys for parents, (vi) guardians ad litem, (vii) a child welfare
26 advocacy organization, (viii) families with experience in the child
27 welfare system, (ix) family caregivers, (x) the Foster Care Review
28 Office, and (xi) the office of Inspector General of Nebraska Child
29 Welfare. Members of the advisory committee shall be appointed for terms
30 of two years. The Nebraska Children's Commission shall appoint the
31 chairperson of the advisory committee and may fill vacancies on the
-2-

LB845 LB845
2026 2026
1 advisory committee as they occur.
2 (2) (3) The department shall adopt and promulgate rules and
3 regulations to carry out this section and sections 28-710.01, 28-712.01,
4 and 28-713. Such rules and regulations shall include, but not be limited
5 to, provisions on (a) the transfer of cases from alternative response to
6 traditional response, (b) notice to families subject to a comprehensive
7 assessment and served through alternative response of the alternative
8 response process and their rights, including the opportunity to challenge
9 agency determinations, (c) the provision of services through alternative
10 response, and (d) the collection, sharing, and reporting of data.
11 Sec. 2. Section 71-561, Revised Statutes Cumulative Supplement,
12 2024, is amended to read:
13 71-561 Sections 71-561 to 71-567 and section 8 of this act shall be
14 known and may be cited as the Aging, Alzheimer's, and Disease and Other
15 Dementia Support Act.
16 Sec. 3. Section 71-563, Revised Statutes Cumulative Supplement,
17 2024, is amended to read:
18 71-563 For purposes of the Aging, Alzheimer's, and Disease and Other
19 Dementia Support Act:
20 (1) Council means the Aging, Alzheimer's, and Dementia Alzheimer's
21 Disease and Other Dementia Advisory Council; and
22 (2) Department means the Department of Health and Human Services.
23 Sec. 4. Section 71-564, Revised Statutes Cumulative Supplement,
24 2024, is amended to read:
25 71-564 (1) The Aging, Alzheimer's, and Dementia Alzheimer's Disease
26 and Other Dementia Advisory Council is created and shall include:
27 (a) Fifteen Twelve voting members appointed by the Governor. The
28 voting members shall consist of: (i) An individual living with
29 Alzheimer's disease or another dementia or a family member of such an
30 individual; (ii) an individual who is the family caregiver of an
31 individual living with Alzheimer's disease or another dementia; (iii) an
-3-

LB845 LB845
2026 2026
1 individual who is a medical professional with experience diagnosing and
2 treating Alzheimer's disease or other dementia represents nursing homes;
3 (iv) an individual who represents assisted-living facilities; (v) an
4 individual who is a representative of a long-term care or community-based
5 aging organization represents providers of adult day care services; (vi)
6 an individual who conducts research related to Alzheimer's disease or
7 other dementia or represents an advocacy organization focused on dementia
8 represents home care providers; (vii) an individual with experience or
9 expertise regarding the needs of individuals with intellectual and
10 developmental disabilities who are aging or living with dementia; and
11 (viii) one representative from each of the eight planning-and-service
12 areas as designated in the Nebraska Community Aging Services Act a
13 medical professional who has experience diagnosing and treating
14 Alzheimer's disease; (viii) an individual who conducts research regarding
15 Alzheimer's disease or other dementia; (ix) an individual who represents
16 a leading, nationwide organization that advocates on behalf of
17 individuals living with Alzheimer's disease or other dementia; (x) an
18 individual who represents an area agency on aging; (xi) an individual
19 representing an organization that advocates for older adults; and (xii)
20 an individual with experience or expertise in the area of the specific
21 needs of individuals with intellectual and developmental disabilities and
22 Alzheimer's disease or other dementia; and
23 (b) Five nonvoting members. The nonvoting members shall consist of:
24 (i) The Director of Public Health or the director's designee; (ii) the
25 Director of Developmental Disabilities Medicaid and Long-Term Care or the
26 director's designee; (iii) the administrator a representative of the
27 State Unit on Aging or the administrator's designee of the Division of
28 Medicaid and Long-Term Care designated by the Director of Medicaid and
29 Long-Term Care; (iv) a representative of the Nebraska Workforce
30 Development Board designated by the board; and (v) the state long-term
31 care ombudsman or the ombudsman's designee.
-4-

LB845 LB845
2026 2026
1 (2) The terms of the initial members shall begin on the date of the
2 first meeting as called by the Director of Public Health and (a) one-
3 third shall serve for two-year terms, (b) one-third shall serve for
4 three-year terms, and (c) one-third shall serve for four-year terms,
5 including the chairperson and vice-chairperson. Thereafter all members
6 shall serve four-year terms. Members may not serve more than two
7 consecutive four-year terms. Vacancies shall be appointed by the Governor
8 in the same manner as described in subdivision (1)(a) of this section.
9 (3) Members of the council shall select the chairperson and vice-
10 chairperson who shall not be employees of the state and may serve in such
11 role for up to four consecutive years. The Director of Public Health or
12 the director's designee shall call and preside over the first meeting
13 until a chairperson is selected. Thereafter, the council shall meet at
14 least quarterly at the call of the chairperson. A majority of the voting
15 members shall constitute a quorum for the conduct of meetings.
16 (4) The council shall hold meetings at least once every calendar
17 quarter.
18 (5) Members shall serve on the council without compensation but
19 shall be compensated for expenses incurred for such service as provided
20 in sections 81-1174 to 81-1177.
21 (6) The department shall provide staff and support to the council as
22 necessary to assist the council in the performance of its duties.
23 Sec. 5. Section 71-565, Revised Statutes Cumulative Supplement,
24 2024, is amended to read:
25 71-565 (1) The purpose of the council shall be to examine (a) the
26 needs of aging individuals and individuals living with Alzheimer's
27 disease or other dementia, (b) the services available in the state for
28 those individuals and their family caregivers, and (c) the ability of
29 health care providers and facilities to meet the current and future needs
30 of such individuals.
31 (2) The council shall collaborate with the department and other
-5-

LB845 LB845
2026 2026
1 state departments as needed to gather input on issues and strategies that
2 pertain to aging, Alzheimer's disease, and other dementia and identify
3 proactive approaches on public health, workforce, caregiver support, and
4 care delivery. The council shall monitor analysis, policy development,
5 and program implementation related to aging, Alzheimer's disease, and
6 other dementia.
7 Sec. 6. Section 71-566, Revised Statutes Cumulative Supplement,
8 2024, is amended to read:
9 71-566 The council shall consider and make findings and
10 recommendations on the following topics:
11 (1) Trends in the state's Alzheimer's disease and other dementia
12 populations and service needs, including:
13 (a) The state's role in providing or facilitating long-term care,
14 family caregiver support, and assistance to those with early-stage or
15 early-onset Alzheimer's disease or other dementia;
16 (b) The state's policies regarding individuals with Alzheimer's
17 disease or other dementia;
18 (c) The fiscal impact of Alzheimer's disease and other dementia on
19 publicly funded health care programs; and
20 (d) The establishment of a surveillance system to better determine
21 the number of individuals diagnosed with Alzheimer's disease or other
22 dementia and to monitor changes to such numbers;
23 (2) Existing resources, services, and capacity relating to the
24 diagnosis and care of individuals living with Alzheimer's disease or
25 other dementia, including:
26 (a) The type, cost, and availability of dementia care services;
27 (b) The availability of health care workers who can serve people
28 with dementia, including, but not limited to, neurologists,
29 geriatricians, and direct care workers;
30 (c) Dementia-specific training requirements for public and private
31 employees who interact with people living with Alzheimer's disease or
-6-

LB845 LB845
2026 2026
1 other dementia which shall include, but not be limited to, long-term care
2 workers, case managers, adult protective services, law enforcement, and
3 first responders;
4 (d) Home and community-based services, including respite care for
5 individuals exhibiting symptoms of Alzheimer's disease or other dementia
6 and their families;
7 (e) Quality care measures for home and community-based services and
8 residential care facilities; and
9 (f) State-supported Alzheimer's disease and other dementia research
10 conducted at universities located in this state; and
11 (3) Policies and strategies that address the following:
12 (a) Increasing public awareness of Alzheimer's disease and other
13 dementia;
14 (b) Educating providers to increase early detection and diagnosis of
15 Alzheimer's disease and other dementia;
16 (c) Improving the health care received by individuals diagnosed with
17 Alzheimer's disease or other dementia;
18 (d) Evaluating the capacity of the health care system in meeting the
19 growing number and needs of those with Alzheimer's disease and other
20 dementia;
21 (e) Increasing the number of health care professionals necessary to
22 treat the growing aging and Alzheimer's disease and dementia populations;
23 (f) Improving services provided in the home and community to delay
24 and decrease the need for institutionalized care for individuals with
25 Alzheimer's disease or other dementia;
26 (g) Improving long-term care, including assisted living, for those
27 with Alzheimer's disease or other dementia;
28 (h) Assisting unpaid Alzheimer's disease or dementia caregivers;
29 (i) Increasing and improving research on Alzheimer's disease and
30 other dementia;
31 (j) Promoting activities to maintain and improve brain health;
-7-

LB845 LB845
2026 2026
1 (k) Improving the collection of data and information related to
2 Alzheimer's disease and other dementia and the resulting public health
3 burdens;
4 (l) Improving public safety and addressing the safety-related needs
5 of those with Alzheimer's disease or other dementia;
6 (m) Addressing legal protections for, and legal issues faced by,
7 individuals with Alzheimer's disease or other dementia; and
8 (n) Improving the ways in which the government evaluates and adopts
9 policies to assist individuals diagnosed with Alzheimer's disease or
10 other dementia and their families; .
11 (4) The collection of facts and statistics and special studies of
12 the conditions and problems pertaining to the employment, health,
13 financial status, recreation, social adjustment, or other conditions and
14 problems relating to the general welfare of aging individuals of the
15 state;
16 (5) State and local agencies serving aging individuals for purposes
17 of coordinating such agencies' activities, and reports from the various
18 state agencies and institutions relating to matters within the
19 jurisdiction of the council;
20 (6) The latest developments of research, studies, and programs being
21 conducted throughout the nation relating to the problems and needs of
22 aging individuals;
23 (7) The mutual exchange of ideas and information relating to aging
24 individuals among federal, state, and local governmental agencies,
25 private organizations, and individuals; and
26 (8) Cooperation with federal, state, and local agencies or private
27 organizations in administering and supervising demonstration programs of
28 services for aging individuals designed to foster continued participation
29 of such individuals in family and community life and to prevent, insofar
30 as possible, the onset of dependency and the need for long-term
31 institutional care.
